Explanation:

1. Initialize an empty vector called "result" with size n (the length of the string s).
2. Iterate through each character of s using a nested loop.
3. For each character, check if the substring starting from that character matches any word in words.
4. If a match is found, update the result for that character to the index of the matching word in words.
5. Return the result vector after iterating through all characters.

This solution has a high efficiency (HIGH) because it uses nested loops to find the indices of the matching words in words. The time complexity is O(n * m * k), where n is the length of s, m is the length of words, and k is the length of the words[j] for j in the inner loop. The space complexity is O(n) because we only use a vector of size n to store the result. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs a few operations and does not consume significant energy.

